Now I understand the problem! The test `testPreserveDOM` expects the value of the element with `xml:space="preserve"` and `id="preserve"` to be `" foo "` (with spaces preserved), but it's probably getting `"foo"` (with spaces trimmed).

Looking at the `stringValue` method in `DOMNodePointer.java`, I can see that it always trims the text values with `.trim()` regardless of the `xml:space` attribute. According to XML specification, when `xml:space="preserve"`, whitespace should be preserved.

Let me look more carefully at the `stringValue` method in the DOMNodePointer class:

```java
private String stringValue(Node node) {
    int nodeType = node.getNodeType();
    if (nodeType == Node.COMMENT_NODE) {
        String text = ((Comment) node).getData();
        return text == null ? "" : text.trim();
    }
    if (nodeType == Node.TEXT_NODE || nodeType == Node.CDATA_SECTION_NODE) {
        String text = node.getNodeValue();
        return text == null ? "" : text.trim();  // <-- This trims regardless of xml:space
    }
    if (nodeType == Node.PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE) {
        String text = ((ProcessingInstruction) node).getData();
        return text == null ? "" : text.trim();
